  "prompt": "Why can't we use ocean water through desalination to provide water to drought hit areas in India?",
  "response": "There are several challenges in using desalination to address water scarcity in India:\n\n1. High Cost\n- Desalination is extremely expensive compared to other water sources\n- Energy-intensive process requires significant electricity\n- High infrastructure and operational costs\n\n2. Energy Requirements\n- Substantial electricity needed for reverse osmosis\n- In a country with energy challenges, this is a major constraint\n- Increases carbon footprint and operational expenses\n\n3. Environmental Concerns\n- Discharge of concentrated salt brine damages marine ecosystems\n- High energy consumption contributes to greenhouse gas emissions\n- Potential negative impact on coastal marine life\n\n4. Technological Limitations\n- Current technologies are not fully efficient\n- Maintenance of desalination plants is complex\n- Requires sophisticated technical expertise\n\n5. Geographic Constraints\n- Not all drought-hit areas are close to coastlines\n- Transportation of desalinated water over long distances is costly\n- Infrastructure challenges in water distribution\n\n6. Economic Feasibility\n- Prohibitively expensive for large-scale implementation\n- Developing countries like India have budget constraints\n- Alternative water management strategies might be more cost-effective\n\nWhile desalination is used in some coastal regions like Gujarat, widespread implementation remains challenging due to these significant technical, economic, and environmental barriers.",
